arch:property.oc:show_val: This locus is fill above a collapsed surface or possible wall in the SE corner of the trench. The fill is softer and looser than topsoil, with the soil becoming identical to topsoil in the northern area of this locus. There are small cobbles (smaller than L4008) scattered with potershrds which appear to be sliding down the slope of the tepe. The northern border of the locus has changed a lot during the dig because we were looking for more collapsed surface area. This border and the south border of L4003 have have mixed on some occasions but the fill is basically the same at this end.
Loose fine silt a bit wetter than the topsoil L4000
The fill in this locu is looser and finer than the topsoi loci and it is about a collapsed surface area. There are some areas north where the soil is identical to topsoil.

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
